author: (Pallas, 1778)
notes: According to Musser & Carleton (in Wilson & Reeder, 2005), Dicrostonyx torquatus was "once believed to encompass most or all New World populations...but karyotypic and breeding evidence...supports strict application of D. torquatus for only Eurasian populations." Thus, D. torquatus identified from North American sites is probably another species. Fulton et al. (2013, Molecular Ecology) used aDNA to indentify D.richardsoni from two sites in South Dakota and Iowa. The specimens from the Iowa site were previously assigned to D. torquatus. [E.C. Grimm, 1 Apr 2013]

author: NA
notes: Based on molecular phylogeny, Piaggio and Spicer (2001) argue that Tamias should be divided into three genera: Eutamias, which includes only Eutamias sibiricus (northern Eurasia); Tamias, which includes only Tamias striatus (eastern North America); and Neotamias, which includes all other species (western North American and Mexico). Thorington & Hoffmann (in Wilson & Reeder, 2005), follow Piaggio and Spicer (2001), but place the three groups as subgenera of Tamias. According to the molecular evidence, the western North American species Tamias minimus (recognized as Eutamias minimus by Kurten and Anderson 1980) is closely related to other western North American chipmunks and should be grouped with them, whether in Tamias or Neotamias. Thus, all species in North America recognized as Eutamias should be referred to Tamias. [ECG, 1 Apr 2013]

author: NA
notes: Muridae is a problematic taxon, and individual reports must be consulted to determine the universe of species included. McKenna and Bell (1997) include all the "muroid" rodents in the Muridae; whereas Musser and Carleton (2005) place the muroids in the superfamily Muroidea and limit the Muridae to a much smaller group of Old World true mice, rats, gerbils, and hamsters. Inasmuch as the Muridae of Musser and Carleton (2005) is Old World, "Muridae" in New World sites probably refers to the muroid rodents in the broad sense. [ECG, 24 Jul 2007]

author: Merriam, 1889
notes: Because of disagreement as to whether some arvicoline species should be placed in Phenacomys or Arborimus (see description of Arborimus in Musser and Carleton 2005), species identified as Phenacomys sp. in the fossil record could be either Phenacomys or Arborimus as defined by Musser and Carleton. Thus, Phenacomys sp. is better treated as Phenacomys/Arborimus sp. [ECG, 27 Jul 2007]
